<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FB48FBDA2A27FB9C" box="[1256,1360,1117,1142]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
); body cylindrical, posteriorly blunt (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FE54FB062D28FB70" box="[500,607,1153,1178]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
), pale, posterior region darker, tiny dots throughout dorsally, medially distorted by the extrusion of gut sectors; 
<quantity id="35189B20325AFF86FD27FB222DABFB57" box="[647,732,1189,1214]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="35189B20325AFF86FC8DFB222CFFFB57" box="[813,904,1189,1214]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage chaetae 
<quantity id="35189B20325AFF86FB48FB222A58FB57" box="[1256,1327,1189,1214]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
long, 58 chaetigers. Body papillae with small and medium sized sediment particles, arranged in 3–4 irregular transverse series per segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325AFF86FF67FA962E63FA7C" blockId="28.[151,1437,793,2006]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Cephalic hood not exposed, but some branchial filaments everted (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FC61FA962B5EFAC0" box="[961,1065,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
; anterior end details observed in 
<typeStatus id="2D5B8867325AFF86FF37FAB22E70FAA4" box="[151,263,1333,1358]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">paratypes</typeStatus>
). Prostomium low, four large brown eyes, anterior ones larger. Caruncle triangular, short. Palps twice as long as branchiae, corrugated; palp lobes rounded, low. Lateral lips well developed, ventral and dorsal lips reduced (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FF3FFAFA2E7FFA7C" box="[159,264,1405,1430]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325AFF86FF67FA262DBAF9E8" blockId="28.[151,1437,793,2006]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Branchiae thick, cirriform, sessile on branchial plate, arranged in two rows, one continuous with four filaments, the other discontinuous with two filaments per side. Nephridial lobes thin, pale, about as long as prostomium, placed internally to lateral branchiae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325AFF86FF67F98A2A68F95F" blockId="28.[151,1437,793,2006]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Cephalic cage chaetae about half as long as body length, over 3x longer than body width. Chaetigers 1–3 forming cephalic cage; chaetae arranged in short series, 7–8 per bundle in chaetiger 1, 9 noto- and 6 neurochaetae in chaetiger 2, and 9 noto- and 6 neurochaetae in chaetiger 3. Chaetigers 1–3 of similar length. Anterior margin of chaetiger 1 with a trifid projection (best preserved in 
<specimenCount id="E4E6FD4C325AFF86FD51F9FD2CF0F978" box="[753,903,1657,1682]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="generic" typeStatus="paratype">one paratype</specimenCount>
). Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; anchylosed, falcate blunt neurohooks start from chaetiger 4. Gonopodial lobes not seen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325AFF86FF67F9462F80F8C8" blockId="28.[151,1437,793,2006]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Parapodia poorly developed, chaetae emerge from body wall. Parapodia lateral; medial neuropodia ventrolateral. Notopodial lobes with two digitate postchaetal papillae. Neuropodial lobes with two postchaetal papillae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325AFF86FF67F8AA2BA6F83F" blockId="28.[151,1437,793,2006]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Medial notochaetae multiarticulated, arranged in a È-pattern, transverse to body axis, directed dorsally; each notochaeta with articles short basally, medium-sized medially, long distally, one marginal notochaeta with all articles long (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FE9CF8F22ED1F864" box="[316,422,1909,1934]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
), about 8 chaetae per fascicle, as long as body width. Neurochaetae multiarticulated capillaries in chaetigers 1–3; anchylosed, falcate yellowish to brown neurohooks from chaetiger 4, arranged in transverse series, 4 per ramus in anterior chaetigers, 
<quantity id="35189B20325AFF86FD43F83A2C5DF83C" box="[739,810,1981,2006]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.89" metricValueMax="10.16" metricValueMin="7.62" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 in</quantity>
medial (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325AFF86FC2CF83A2C9AF83C" box="[908,1005,1981,2006]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-304@29.[169,1417,193,1263]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pherusa nipponica n. sp. A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10F</figureCitation>
) and posterior ones.
</paragraph>
<caption id="A69F664D325BFF87FF37FA832DEDFA5E" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951940" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4951940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951940/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" startId="29.[151,250,1284,1306]" targetBox="[173,1415,197,1260]" targetPageId="29">
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF37FA832DEDFA5E" blockId="29.[151,1436,1284,1460]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF37FA832E6BFAF0" bold="true" box="[151,284,1284,1306]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">FIGURE 10</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FE8BFA832E99FAF0" authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[299,494,1284,1306]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FE8BFA832E99FAF0" box="[299,494,1284,1306]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pherusa nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FE57FA832D43FAF0" bold="true" box="[503,564,1284,1306]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="DBA757AC325BFF87FE57FA832D43FAF0" box="[503,564,1284,1306]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A. Holotype (CMNH 305), before being brushed-off, anterior end, dorsal view. B. Same, after removal of foreign materials, anterior end, slightly oblique dorsal view. C. Same, posterior end, oblique dorsal view. D. Paratype (CMNH 1534), head, frontal view (branchiae and palps removed; BS: branchial scar, LL: lateral lip, NL: nephridial lobe, PS: palp scar). E. Same, chaetiger 10, right parapodium, anterior view, some chaetae broken (insets: basal and distal notochaetal regions; neurochaetae). F. Same, chaetiger 35, left parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 1.1 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 1.0 mm, D: 190 µm, E: 260 µm, F: 80 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF67FA5C2C2AF9F2" blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Posterior end with long chaetae, chaetae about as long as body width, shorter terminally (
<figureCitation id="6ADB2A40325BFF87FB61FA5C2A6CFA1E" box="[1217,1307,1499,1524]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1118,1140]" captionTargetBox="[173,1411,196,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-310@27.[169,1417,193,1097]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 9. Pherusa neopapillata Hartman, 1961. A. Holotype (LACM 531), lateral view. B. Paratype (LACM 532), anterior end, dorsal view, some sand particles removed. C. Same, chaetiger 11, notochaetae. D. Same, chaetiger 6, right parapodium, neurochaetae. E. Same, chaetiger 27, right parapodium, neurochaetae. Scale bars: A: 0.8 mm, B: 0.9 mm, C: 0.4 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951934/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
); pygidium conical, truncate, anus slightly projected, whitish, without cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BAFA654E325BFF87FF67F9A42A36F926" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF67F9A42A36F926" blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF67F9A42E4CF9D6" bold="true" box="[199,315,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Remarks.</emphasis>
As indicated in the key above, 
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FD0AF9A42CF7F9D1" authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[682,896,1571,1596]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FD0AF9A42CF7F9D1" box="[682,896,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pherusa nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FC29F9A42CBDF9D6" bold="true" box="[905,970,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="DBA757AC325BFF87FC29F9A42CBDF9D6" box="[905,970,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FBECF9A32A00F9D6" authority="(Muller, 1776)" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[1100,1399,1571,1596]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosa">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FBECF9A32BBFF9D6" box="[1100,1224,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. plumosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="96714B34325BFF87FB79F9A42A18F9D6" author="Muller, O. F." box="[1241,1391,1571,1596]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref49681" refString="Muller, O. F. (1776) Zoologiae Danicae Prodromus, seu Animalium Daniae et Norvegiae indigenarum. Characteres, nomina et synonyma imprimis popularium. Hallageriis, Havniae (Copenhagen), 274 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13268" type="book" year="1776">Müller, 1776</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
by having body papillae covered by only fine sediment particles. There are two main differences between these two species: the number of transverse series of papillae per segment, and the shape (and colour) of their neurohooks. In 
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FF37F9172E55F94D" authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,290,1680,1703]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nipponica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF37F9172E55F94D" box="[151,290,1680,1703]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. nipponica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FE88F9082E11F942" bold="true" box="[296,358,1679,1704]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="DBA757AC325BFF87FE88F9082E11F942" box="[296,358,1679,1704]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
there are 3–4 series, and neurohooks are yellowish to brown and markedly curved, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FA27F9172F81F926" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosa">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FA27F9172F81F926" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. plumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are 6–8 transverse series of papillae, and neurohooks are brownish and only slightly falcate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BAFA654E325BFF87FF67F9502DDFF8F9" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF67F9502DDFF8F9" blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF67F9502E39F91A" bold="true" box="[199,334,1751,1776]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the original name of the country, 
<collectingCountry id="8AF77655325BFF87FBEAF9502BD6F91A" box="[1098,1185,1751,1776]" name="Japan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Nippon</collectingCountry>
, with a suffix to fit the gender of the generic name, meaning Japanese.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BAFA654E325BFF87FF67F8982D4CF8DD" box="[199,571,1823,1848]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF67F8982D4CF8DD" blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" box="[199,571,1823,1848]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<materialsCitation id="42883C98325BFF87FF67F8982D40F8DD" box="[199,567,1823,1848]" country="Japan" location="Bay" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Tokyo" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF67F8982E12F8D2" bold="true" box="[199,357,1823,1848]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<typeStatus id="2D5B8867325BFF87FF67F8982E75F8D2" box="[199,258,1823,1848]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Type</typeStatus>
locality.
</emphasis>
<collectingRegion id="3024F827325BFF87FECCF8982EC4F8D2" box="[364,435,1823,1848]" country="Japan" name="Tokyo" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Tokyo</collectingRegion>
<location id="F73F601E325BFF87FE1AF8A72E9FF8D2" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:7A4987D3325AFF87FF37FDEB2A41F86A:F73F601E325BFF87FE1AF8A72E9FF8D2" box="[442,488,1824,1848]" country="Japan" name="Bay" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" stateProvince="Tokyo">Bay</location>
, 
<collectingCountry id="8AF77655325BFF87FE53F8A72D40F8DD" box="[499,567,1824,1847]" name="Japan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Japan</collectingCountry>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BAFA654E325BFF87FF67F8C42A41F86A" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F25F36C5325BFF87FF67F8C42A41F86A" blockId="29.[151,1440,1499,1920]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FF67F8C42E17F8B6" bold="true" box="[199,352,1859,1884]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Distribution.</emphasis>
Although currently known only from the above localities in shelf depths (
<quantity id="35189B20325BFF87FB73F8C42A2CF8B6" box="[1235,1371,1859,1884]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.55" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="m" value="255.0" valueMax="260.0" valueMin="250.0">250–260 m</quantity>
), this species may be more widespread in Japanese waters, where it might have been confused with 
<emphasis id="C094EAD7325BFF87FB14F8EF2A41F86A" box="[1204,1334,1895,1920]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName id="35E04D46325BFF87FB14F8EF2A46F86A" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[1204,1329,1895,1920]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosa">P. plumosa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
